Rule tells us.

00:58:24.030 --> 00:58:28.010
I want to now derive this
situation for you for our atom

00:58:28.010 --> 00:58:30.240
in the cavity.

00:58:30.240 --> 00:58:33.950
And I will say that this is one
example for the quantum Zeno

00:58:33.950 --> 00:58:35.180
effect.

00:58:35.180 --> 00:58:36.860
But let me already
explain to you

00:58:36.860 --> 00:58:39.260
what the quantum Zeno effect is.

00:58:39.260 --> 00:58:41.490
Zeno is a Greek philosopher.

00:58:41.490 --> 00:58:46.620
And the Greek philosophers
had some deep thoughts

00:58:46.620 --> 00:58:49.910
about the nature of time,
the nature of motion.

00:58:49.910 --> 00:58:52.220
And I think, in the
Greek philosophy-- sorry.

00:58:54.820 --> 00:58:59.635
I didn't go-- I mean, I don't
have a strong background

00:58:59.635 --> 00:59:01.780
in philosophy, but
I think the idea

00:59:01.780 --> 00:59:05.640
is that motion is when
something moves around.

00:59:05.640 --> 00:59:07.550
But it takes some time to move.

00:59:07.550 --> 00:59:10.180
So if you observe
it, it can't move,

00:59:10.180 --> 00:59:13.514
because every time you observe
it, you localize something.

00:59:13.514 --> 00:59:14.180
That's the idea.

00:59:14.180 --> 00:59:17.610
If you see an arrow, the moment
you observe it, it's localized.

00:59:17.610 --> 00:59:21.170
And if you localize something
to often, it cannot move.

00:59:21.170 --> 00:59:23.590
And this is sort of
what you can say here.

00:59:23.590 --> 00:59:26.700
The system wants to
evolve to a second state.

00:59:26.700 --> 00:59:30.010
But kappa can actually
be a measurement process.

00:59:30.010 --> 00:59:32.640
We can just shine a
strong laser on this state

00:59:32.640 --> 00:59:35.360
and figure out has
something arrived here.

00:59:35.360 --> 00:59:41.340
And the more often we look, the
stronger our measurement is,

00:59:41.340 --> 00:59:44.340
the less the system can evolve.

00:59:44.340 --> 00:59:47.970
So a measurement of what
arrives in this state

00:59:47.970 --> 00:59:51.570
slows down the
dynamics to that state.

00:59:51.570 --> 00:59:53.720
And this is called the
quantum Zeno effect.

00:59:53.720 --> 00:59:56.450
It also goes by the name
of quantum Zeno paradox.

00:59:56.450 --> 01:00:00.680
But it's just quantum
mechanics, it's not a paradox.

01:00:00.680 --> 01:00:03.930
In the popular world, it
is sometimes paraphrased

01:00:03.930 --> 01:00:09.470
as if you observe the tea
kettle, the water never boils.

01:00:09.470 --> 01:00:13.220
But you see now
where it comes from.

01:00:13.220 --> 01:00:15.200
OK, so this is the
quantum Zeno effect.

01:00:15.200 --> 01:00:18.470
And we want to now, by
looking at the master

01:00:18.470 --> 01:00:20.990
equation for an
atom in a cavity,

01:00:20.990 --> 01:00:22.910
I want to show you the
limit that it really

01:00:22.910 --> 01:00:25.640
comes out of the
master equation.

01:00:25.640 --> 01:00:26.850
Questions about that?

01:00:43.260 --> 01:00:49.720
OK, so this is the
quantum Zeno effect.

01:00:49.720 --> 01:00:56.680
And well, one of the nicest
papers on the quantum Zeno

01:00:56.680 --> 01:01:00.820
effect-- well, I'm biased here--
but it was written by my group,

01:01:00.820 --> 01:01:04.240
because we used the
Bose-Einstein condensate.

01:01:04.240 --> 01:01:08.450
We had an RF coupling to
another hyperfine state.

01:01:08.450 --> 01:01:15.840
And then we used a laser beam
and observed the population

01:01:15.840 --> 01:01:17.050
in the final state.

01:01:17.050 --> 01:01:21.070
And we saw that the
effect of the RF drive

01:01:21.070 --> 01:01:23.820
became weaker and
weaker and weaker,

01:01:23.820 --> 01:01:28.278
