stronger we damp the cavity,

01:11:13.910 --> 01:11:17.850
the smaller, the weaker, is
the decay of the initial state.

01:11:26.360 --> 01:11:28.940
And I've already
explained to you

01:11:28.940 --> 01:11:33.690
that one picture to explain
that is that we have the excited

01:11:33.690 --> 01:11:37.780
state, we have the ground state.

01:11:37.780 --> 01:11:42.640
The ground state
gets damped by kappa.

01:11:42.640 --> 01:11:48.350
And therefore, the
time evolution,

01:11:48.350 --> 01:11:51.360
which is given by the vacuum
Rabi oscillation, slows down.

01:11:56.780 --> 01:11:57.280
OK.

01:12:04.560 --> 01:12:05.100
Yes.

01:12:05.100 --> 01:12:05.683
Any questions?

01:12:12.260 --> 01:12:18.010
So we have now resolved
for gamma cavity.

01:12:18.010 --> 01:12:21.980
We have a result
how the atom decays

01:12:21.980 --> 01:12:23.480
in the presence of the cavity.

01:12:26.990 --> 01:12:30.840
And I want to rewrite this
for you in a very nice way.

01:12:30.840 --> 01:12:34.230
Namely, I want to show
you the famous result

01:12:34.230 --> 01:12:38.070
that, when an atom
emits in a cavity,

01:12:38.070 --> 01:12:43.140
that the atom can decay faster
than the spontaneous decay.

01:12:43.140 --> 01:12:45.440
Because if the cavity
has a resonance,

01:12:45.440 --> 01:12:49.230
the cavity changes the
vacuum around the atom.

01:12:49.230 --> 01:12:51.450
It increases the
density of modes.

01:12:51.450 --> 01:12:53.160
And therefore, there
is a stimulation

01:12:53.160 --> 01:12:56.120
of the atom into the cavity.

01:12:56.120 --> 01:12:58.450
So I don't have to
do any other math

01:12:58.450 --> 01:13:03.550
than just rewriting our result
of gamma cavity in other units,

01:13:03.550 --> 01:13:04.470
in other ways.

01:13:04.470 --> 01:13:08.419
And then we can compare it to
the natural decay of an atom

01:13:08.419 --> 01:13:09.210
without the cavity.

01:13:11.770 --> 01:13:14.600
So what we want to
do now is we want

01:13:14.600 --> 01:13:25.300
to take the cavity-induced
decay of the excited state,

01:13:25.300 --> 01:13:33.170
and we want to compare with
the natural decay rate, gamma.

01:13:33.170 --> 01:13:38.350
So I just have to rewrite
things in a few units.

01:13:38.350 --> 01:13:43.250
The cavity-induced decay is
the vacuum Rabi oscillation

01:13:43.250 --> 01:13:45.025
squared over kappa.

01:13:49.450 --> 01:13:57.350
So let me remind you that
the Rabi frequency is always

01:13:57.350 --> 01:14:01.320
given by an dipole moment
times electric field.

01:14:01.320 --> 01:14:03.710
It's a matrix element.

01:14:03.710 --> 01:14:05.770
Well, there's one of
those factors of 2.

01:14:05.770 --> 01:14:08.680
And H bar keeps
the units correct.

01:14:08.680 --> 01:14:13.030
And in the case of the
vacuum Rabi oscillation,

01:14:13.030 --> 01:14:18.660
the electric field is the
electric field, so to speak,

01:14:18.660 --> 01:14:24.230
of one photon in
the cavity volume.

01:14:24.230 --> 01:14:27.460
And there is a factor
of 2, so this is now

01:14:27.460 --> 01:14:30.600
the volume of the cavity.

01:14:34.320 --> 01:14:44.555
So therefore, the
vacuum Rabi frequency

01:14:44.555 --> 01:14:54.330
is a dipole moment
times 2 atomic resonance

01:14:54.330 --> 01:14:58.570
frequency epsilon 0 h bar v.

01:14:58.570 --> 01:15:02.250
And that means now-- and
this is a nice result--

01:15:02.250 --> 01:15:09.540
that the cavity-induced decay
is omega 0 square over kappa.

01:15:09.540 --> 01:15:13.870
And I just use the above
result for omega 0.

01:15:13.870 --> 01:15:19.260
And for kappa, I
introduce the Q factor

01:15:19.260 --> 01:15:22.900
of the cavity, which is
the number of oscillations

01:15:22.900 --> 01:15:24.130
before it is damped.

01:15:24.130 --> 01:15:26.310
It's omega over kappa.

01:15:26.310 --> 01:15:31.200
And with that, I can rewrite
the cavity-induced decay

01:15:31.200 --> 01:15:38.300
as 2d squared epsilon
null H bar v times Q.

01:15:38.300 --> 01:15:41.620
And if you remember, from
part 1 of the course,

01:15:41.620 --> 01:15:45.420
or standard textbook result,
that spontaneous decay is

01:15:45.420 --> 01:15:59.923
a dipole moment squared times
frequency to the power 3,

01:15:59.923 --> 01:16:06.680
then we obtain
the famous result,

01:16:06.680 --> 01:16:13.220
which is called the
Purcell factor, namely

01:16:13.220 --> 01:16:17.410
that the decay in
the cavity, compared

01:16:17.410 --> 01:16:22.570
to the decay in free space,
is proportional to the Q

01:16:22.570 --> 01:16:23.295
of the cavity.

01:16:27.400 --> 01:16:30.550
There is a numerical prefector.

