But then, what enters
is the wavelength

01:16:33.080 --> 01:16:35.240
of the photon cubed
over the volume.

01:16:42.670 --> 01:16:47.290
So the case of eta
larger than 1--

01:16:47.290 --> 01:16:51.010
and it's actually interesting
that this result is completely

01:16:51.010 --> 01:16:52.645
independent of
atomic properties.

01:16:58.280 --> 01:17:00.810
So in other words, every
atom you put in a cavity,

01:17:00.810 --> 01:17:03.340
no matter what its
dipole moment is,

01:17:03.340 --> 01:17:11.360
it will decay with a rate
which is Q times larger.

01:17:14.387 --> 01:17:15.970
There are many ways
how to look at it.

01:17:15.970 --> 01:17:19.720
You can say, if the cavity
consists of two mirrors,

01:17:19.720 --> 01:17:24.960
you create Q mirror
images of your atom.

01:17:24.960 --> 01:17:26.390
And you have sort
of an atom which

01:17:26.390 --> 01:17:28.280
has a Q times stronger
dipole moment.

01:17:28.280 --> 01:17:31.570
And therefore, because the
mirror images also radiate,

01:17:31.570 --> 01:17:33.710
and therefore you get
a Q times faster decay.

01:17:33.710 --> 01:17:36.990
So this limit makes sense in
many, many different pictures.

01:17:36.990 --> 01:17:39.720
And it's a general result
that, if an atom emits

01:17:39.720 --> 01:17:43.050
in a cavity with finesse
Q, you get a Q times

01:17:43.050 --> 01:17:46.780
enhancement of
spontaneous decay.

01:17:46.780 --> 01:17:55.680
So this is called
cavity-enhanced spontaneous

01:17:55.680 --> 01:17:57.680
emission.

01:17:57.680 --> 01:18:04.420
It goes back to Purcell in 1946.

01:18:04.420 --> 01:18:11.850
And you can see the
whole field of cavity QED

01:18:11.850 --> 01:18:16.730
depends on this effect, that you
can enhance spontaneous decay.

01:18:16.730 --> 01:18:19.580
Or it's the opposite.

01:18:19.580 --> 01:18:21.430
If an atom has a
resonance frequency

01:18:21.430 --> 01:18:24.450
between two modes of the
cavity, the spontaneous decay

01:18:24.450 --> 01:18:26.930
is inhibited.

01:18:26.930 --> 01:18:29.710
And this is sort of what
is exploited in cavity QED.

01:18:32.770 --> 01:18:37.800
Let me just conclude
here by saying

01:18:37.800 --> 01:18:40.656
that our assumptions
have to be consistent.

01:18:43.860 --> 01:18:49.160
In our derivation,
we neglected gamma.

01:18:49.160 --> 01:18:51.780
When I said the two
Lindblad operators,

01:18:51.780 --> 01:18:53.910
we only look at the
leakage out of the photon.

01:18:53.910 --> 01:18:57.750
We neglect spontaneous decay.

01:18:57.750 --> 01:19:02.120
So of course, this requires
that eta is larger 1.

01:19:02.120 --> 01:19:09.390
So this is the consistent range
of validity of our result.

01:19:09.390 --> 01:19:16.410
Secondly, we discussed
the limit of overdamping,

01:19:16.410 --> 01:19:20.420
which requires that kappa has to
be larger than the vacuum Rabi

01:19:20.420 --> 01:19:21.900
frequency.

01:19:21.900 --> 01:19:32.090
And therefore, the above
result is valued for large Q.

01:19:32.090 --> 01:19:34.770
Q has to be sufficiently large,
but cannot be larger than this

01:19:34.770 --> 01:19:35.270
value.

01:19:39.970 --> 01:19:41.330
Any questions?

01:19:43.910 --> 01:19:44.805
