01:19:44.805 --> 01:19:49.170
AUDIENCE: For kappa, is that
the loss in the cavity--

01:19:49.170 --> 01:19:51.595
is there any difference
between the loss and the cavity

01:19:51.595 --> 01:19:53.050
because it's a cavity?

01:19:53.050 --> 01:19:57.415
Or the loss is into other
modes of the cavity?

01:19:57.415 --> 01:19:59.810
PROFESSOR: Kappa is the loss.

01:19:59.810 --> 01:20:03.745
You can say kappa is the rate
at which a photon in the cavity

01:20:03.745 --> 01:20:04.430
is lost.

01:20:04.430 --> 01:20:06.269
AUDIENCE: Is lost from
the cavity totally?

01:20:06.269 --> 01:20:09.213
Or is lost into another
mode inside the cavity?

01:20:09.213 --> 01:20:10.213
Is there any difference?

01:20:10.213 --> 01:20:15.143
Is v here just one
mode inside the cavity.

01:20:15.143 --> 01:20:18.290
PROFESSOR: Well, we
have not an element--

01:20:18.290 --> 01:20:22.390
OK, if the mirror
has imperfections,

01:20:22.390 --> 01:20:25.850
we usually think of light
leaking out of the mirror.

01:20:25.850 --> 01:20:28.780
If the mirror is absorbing
because the coating has

01:20:28.780 --> 01:20:31.440
a tiny little bit
of absorption, you

01:20:31.440 --> 01:20:33.530
know, from the beam
splitter analogy,

01:20:33.530 --> 01:20:36.830
that a small absorption
is equivalent here

01:20:36.830 --> 01:20:39.740
to a small transmission factor.

01:20:39.740 --> 01:20:43.200
Usually, we don't consider
that the light transforms

01:20:43.200 --> 01:20:45.030
from one mode of the
cavity to the other.

01:20:45.030 --> 01:20:47.350
It's either absorbed
or leaking out.

01:20:47.350 --> 01:20:50.460
But if you assume that the
mirrors are not super polished

01:20:50.460 --> 01:20:52.440
and they scatter
light a little bit,

01:20:52.440 --> 01:20:54.940
then you would have a mechanism
that the light in the cavity

01:20:54.940 --> 01:20:56.330
scatters into other modes.

01:20:56.330 --> 01:20:58.780
And all those losses
are summarized

01:20:58.780 --> 01:21:00.730
in one coupling constant, kappa.

01:21:04.690 --> 01:21:08.860
