01:21:17.860 --> 01:21:22.430
And the Lindblad
operators, the dissipation,

01:21:22.430 --> 01:21:25.230
tells us what is the
effect of the environment.

01:21:25.230 --> 01:21:28.210
And usually, you would say,
well, if you have an atom,

01:21:28.210 --> 01:21:30.270
and it interacts
with the environment,

01:21:30.270 --> 01:21:33.110
what is the equilibrium state?

01:21:33.110 --> 01:21:35.060
Well, if you just
have the vacuum,

01:21:35.060 --> 01:21:36.710
the atom goes to
the ground state.

01:21:36.710 --> 01:21:39.090
And the ground state
is the attractor,

01:21:39.090 --> 01:21:41.050
the stable state of the system.

01:21:41.050 --> 01:21:43.960
If you drive the system
with one laser beam,

01:21:43.960 --> 01:21:46.970
the attractor state where
the system goes into

01:21:46.970 --> 01:21:50.560
is the steady state solution
of the optical Bloch equation.

01:21:50.560 --> 01:21:52.700
That all sounds a
little bit boring.

01:21:52.700 --> 01:21:56.190
But in this paper, based on
this theoretical suggestion

01:21:56.190 --> 01:21:59.020
of Peter Zola and an
experimental realization

01:21:59.020 --> 01:22:02.930
with trapped ions at
Innsbrook, they actually

01:22:02.930 --> 01:22:08.120
engineered an environment,
engineered Lindblad operators

01:22:08.120 --> 01:22:11.770
in such a way that
the system of two ions

01:22:11.770 --> 01:22:15.930
was relaxing into a Bell state.

01:22:15.930 --> 01:22:18.290
So you engineer
now the environment

01:22:18.290 --> 01:22:23.020
that therm-- I wanted to say
thermal equilibrium, no--

01:22:23.020 --> 01:22:26.740
the equilibrium state with the
environment, the dissipation,

01:22:26.740 --> 01:22:29.640
leads to a Bell state.

01:22:29.640 --> 01:22:32.740
Well, it's a little bit
complicated how it is done,

01:22:32.740 --> 01:22:39.340
but I just want to just look at
a few highlighted key messages.

01:22:39.340 --> 01:22:44.120
So the idea is, here,
engineering of dissipation,

01:22:44.120 --> 01:22:47.170
creating experimentally
dissipative operators.

01:22:47.170 --> 01:22:50.530
We usually manipulate quantum
system with Hamilton operators.

01:22:50.530 --> 01:22:55.850
But here, it is manipulated
not by the H operator,

01:22:55.850 --> 01:22:58.670
but by the L operator.

01:22:58.670 --> 01:23:04.810
And so the idea here is to have
an evolution of the density

01:23:04.810 --> 01:23:07.900
matrix, a linear mapping that
the density matrix evolves

01:23:07.900 --> 01:23:10.820
in a certain way.

01:23:10.820 --> 01:23:12.850
I think you'll
recognize partial trace.

01:23:12.850 --> 01:23:16.400
You'll recognize
a few equations,

01:23:16.400 --> 01:23:19.840
a few results which
we have discussed.

01:23:19.840 --> 01:23:23.650
And what you see here is
exactly the Lindblad form.

01:23:23.650 --> 01:23:26.540
And what they did is, by
using a number of laser

01:23:26.540 --> 01:23:33.090
beams in quantum operation,
they designed operators, z,

01:23:33.090 --> 01:23:36.300
jump operators, Lindblad
operators, in such a way

01:23:36.300 --> 01:23:42.080
that the system was damping
out into a Bell state.

01:23:42.080 --> 01:23:46.730
So that seems a new
frontier for research.

01:23:46.730 --> 01:23:50.160
It goes by the title that we
can do quantum simulations,

01:23:50.160 --> 01:23:53.880
using trapped ions and
cold atoms of Hamiltonians.

01:23:53.880 --> 01:23:58.200
But we can also quantum simulate
very special environments.

01:23:58.200 --> 01:24:00.560
Maybe environments
which it would

01:24:00.560 --> 01:24:03.190
be hard to find them
in nature, but they

01:24:03.190 --> 01:24:07.260
are quantum-mechanically
allowed possible environments.

01:24:07.260 --> 01:24:09.040
And they may have
new features which

01:24:09.040 --> 01:24:10.290
have not been explored so far.

